         <abstract>
            <p>We consider the question of the approximation of nonnegative functions by nonnegative splines of order $k (\text{degree} &lt; k)$ compared with approximation by that subclass of nonnegative splines of order $k$ consisting of all those whose $B$-spline coefficients are nonnegative; while approximation by the former gives errors of order $h^k$, the latter may yield only $h^2$. These results are related to certain facts about quasi-interpolants.</p>
          </abstract>
